Definition 7.1. Let $P$ be a semigroupoid, Then $P$ is (1) a prepoloid when there is a local left unit $\lambda_{x}\in P$ and a local right unit $\rho_{x}\in P$ for every $x\in P$; (2) a pregroupoid10Kock [11] lets the term ’pregroupoid’ refer to a set with a partially defined ternary operation. when $P$ is a prepoloid such that for every $x\in P$ there is a preinverse $x^{-1}\in P$ of $x$. This means that a prepoloid is a semigroupoid such that for every $x\in P$ there are local units $\lambda{}_{x},\rho{}_{x}$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\lambda{}_{x}x}\right)=x=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{% }\left(x\rho{}_{x}}\right)$. A pregroupoid is a prepoloid $P$ such that for every $x\in P$ there is some $x^{-1}\in P$ such that there are units $\lambda_{x},\rho_{x}$ such that$\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{-1}}\right)\in\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left% \{\lambda}\right\}_{x}\cap\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\rho}\right\}_{x^{-1}}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)\in\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left% \{\rho}\right\}_{x}\cap\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\lambda}\right\}_{x^{-1}}$.
Definition 5.2. A (total) involution magmoid is a magmoid $P$ equipped with a total mapping $*:P\rightarrow P,\qquad x\mapsto*\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x}\right)=:x^{*}$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{*}}\right)^{*}=x$ and if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)^{*}}% \right)=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(y^{*}x^{*}}\right)$ for all $x,y\in P$. We call the function $x\mapsto x^{*}$ an involution and $x^{*}$ the involute of $x$.
Definition 8.1. Let $P$ be a prepoloid with binary operation $\mathfrak{m}:\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)\mapsto\mathopen{}% \mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$, $x,y\in P$. The restricted binary operation on the carrier set of $P$ is a binary operation $\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}:\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)\mapsto% \mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ such that if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(% xy}\right)$, and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ if and only if relative to $\mathfrak{m}$ there is some $\rho_{x}\in\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\rho}\right\}_{x}$ and some $\lambda_{y}\in\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\lambda}\right\}_{y}$ such that $\rho_{x}=\lambda_{y}$. The core $P\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left[\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}}\right]$ of $P$ is $P$ with $\mathfrak{m}$ replaced by $\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}$.
Definition 4.2. Let $P$ be a magmoid, $x\in P$. (1) A (global) left unit is some $\epsilon\in P$ such that if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\epsilon x}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\epsilon x}\right)=x$, while a (global) right unit is some $\varepsilon\in P$ such that if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\varepsilon}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\varepsilon}\right)=x$. (2) A (global) two-sided unit is some $e\in P$ which is a (global) left unit and a (global) right unit.
Definition 2.1. A functional relation, or (partial) mapping, $\mathfrak{f}:X\rightarrow Y$ is a binary relation $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\phi,X,Y}\right)$ such that for each $x\in\mathrm{pr}_{1}\,\phi$ there is exactly one $y\in\mathrm{pr}_{2}\,\phi$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)\in\phi$. A self-mapping on $X$ is a mapping $\mathfrak{f}:X\rightarrow X$.
Definition 4.3. Let $P$ be a magmoid, $x\in P$. (1) A local left unit for $x$ is some $\lambda_{x}\in P$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\lambda_{x}x}\right)=x$; a local right unit for $x$ is some $\rho_{x}\in P$ such that $x=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\rho_{x}}\right)$. (2) A twisted left unit $\varphi_{x}\in P$ for $x$ is a local left unit for $x$ which is a right unit, while a twisted right unit $\psi_{x}\in P$ for $x$ is a local right unit for $x$ which is a left unit. (3) A left effective unit $\ell_{x}\in P$ for $x$ is a local left unit for $x$ which is a two-sided unit, while a right effective unit $r_{x}\in P$ for $x$ is a local right unit for $x$ which is a two-sided unit. We denote the set of local left (resp. local right) units for $x\in P$ by $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\lambda}\right\}_{x}$ (resp. $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\rho}\right\}_{x}$), the set of twisted left (resp. twisted right) units for $x\in P$ by $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\varphi}\right\}_{x}$ (resp. $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\psi}\right\}_{x}$), and the set of left effective (resp. right effective) units for $x\in P$ by $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\ell}\right\}_{x}$ (resp. $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{r}\right\}_{x}$).
Definition 8.3. Let $P$ be a left skew-prepoloid with a binary operation $\mathfrak{m}:\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)\mapsto\mathopen{}% \mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$, $x,y\in P$. The restricted multiplication on the carrier set of $P$ is a binary operation $\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}:\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)\mapsto% \mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ such that if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(% xy}\right)$, and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ if and only if there is some local left unit $\lambda_{y}$ for $y$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\lambda_{y}}\right)=x$. The core $P\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left[\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}}\right]$ of $P$ is $P$ with $\mathfrak{m}$ replaced by $\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}$.
Definition 5.1. An idempotent in a magmoid $P$ is some $i\in P$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(ii}\right)=i$.
Definition 6.1. Let $P$ be a semigroupoid. Then $P$ is (1) a poloid7The term “poloid” for a generalized monoid was introduced and motivated in [9]. when there is a left effective unit $\ell_{x}\in P$ and a right effective unit $r_{x}\in P$ for every $x\in P$; (2) a groupoid when $P$ is a poloid such that for every $x\in P$ and any $\ell_{x},r_{x}\in P$ there is a preinverse $x^{-1}\in P$ of $x$ relative to $\ell_{x},r_{x}$.
Definition 7.2. Let $P$ be a left (resp. right) semigroupoid. Then $P$ is (1) a left (resp. right) skew-prepoloid when there is a local left (resp. right) unit $\lambda_{x}\in P$ (resp. $\rho_{x}\in P$) for every $x\in P$; (2) a left (resp. right) skew-pregroupoid when $P$ is a left (resp. right) skew-prepoloid such that for each $x\in P$ there is a right (resp. left) preinverse $x^{-1}$ of $x$ in $P$. In view of the left-right duality of these notions, it suffices to consider left skew-prepoloids and left skew-pregroupoids. By Definition 7.2, a left skew-prepoloid is a left semigroupoid $P$ such that for every $x\in P$ there is some $\lambda{}_{x}\in P$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\lambda{}_{x}x}\right)=x$. A left skew-groupoid is a left skew-poloid $P$ such that for every $x\in P$ there is some $x^{-1}\in P$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{-1}}\right)\!\in\!\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}% \left\{\lambda}\right\}_{x}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)\!\in\!\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}% \left\{\lambda}\right\}_{x^{-1}}$, so that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{-1}}\right)x}% \right)\!=\!x$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)x^{% -1}}\right)\!=\!x^{-1}$.
Definition 5.3. A unity in a magmoid $P$ with involution $*$ is some $u\in P$ such that $u^{*}=u$.
Definition 4.5. Let $P$ be a magmoid, $x\in P$. Let $u_{x}$ be a twisted left unit or left effective unit for $x$, and let $v_{x}$ be a twisted right unit or right effective unit for $x$. (1) A pseudoinverse of $x$ relative to $u_{x},v_{x}$ is a pseudoinverse $x^{\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(-1}\right)}$ of $x$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(-1}\right)}}% \right)=u_{x}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(-1}\right)}x}% \right)=v_{x}$. (2) A preinverse of $x$ relative to $u_{x}$ is a right preinverse $x^{-1}$ of $x$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{-1}}\right)=u_{x}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)=u_{x^{-1}}$. (3) A preinverse of $x$ relative to $v_{x}$ is a left preinverse $x^{-1}$ of $x$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)=v{}_{x}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{-1}}\right)=v_{x^{-1}}$. (4) A preinverse of $x$ relative to $u_{x},v_{x}$ is a preinverse $x^{-1}$ of $x$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{-1}}\right)=u_{x}=v_{x^{-1}}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)=v_{x}=u_{x^{-1}}$.
Definition 8.2. Let $P$ be a pregroupoid with binary operation $\mathfrak{m}:\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)\mapsto\mathopen{}% \mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$, $x,y\in P$. The restricted binary operation on the carrier set of $P$ is a binary operation $\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}}:\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)% \mapsto\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ such that if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(% xy}\right)$, and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ if and only if there is a canonical local right unit $\boldsymbol{\uprho}_{x}=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)$ for $x$ and a canonical local left unit $\boldsymbol{\uplambda}_{y}=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yy^{-1}}\right)$ for $y$ such that $\boldsymbol{\uprho}_{x}=\boldsymbol{\uplambda}_{y}$. The core $P\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left[\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}}\right]$ of $P$ is $P$ with $\mathfrak{m}$ replaced by $\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}$.
Definition 6.2. Let $P$ be a left (resp. right) semigroupoid. Then $P$ is (1) a left (resp. right) skew-poloid when there is a unique twisted left (resp. right) unit $\varphi_{x}\in P$ (resp. $\psi_{x}\in P$) for every $x\in P$; (2) a left (right) skew-groupoid when $P$ is a left (resp. right) poloid such that for every $x\in P$ there is a preinverse $x^{-1}\in P$ relative to $\varphi_{x}$ (resp. $\psi_{x}$).
Definition 2.2. A (partial) binary operation on a non-empty set $X$ is a non-empty (partial) mapping $\mathfrak{m}:X\times X\rightarrow X,\qquad\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}% \right)\mapsto\mathfrak{m}\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)=:xy.$ A total binary operation on $X$ is a total mapping $\mathfrak{m}:X\times X\rightarrow X$. A magmoid is a non-empty set $X$ equipped with a (partial) binary operation on $X$; a total magmoid, or magma, is a non-empty set $X$ equipped with a total binary operation on $X$.
Definition 8.4. Let $P$ be a left skew-pregroupoid with binary operation $\mathfrak{m}:\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)\mapsto\mathopen{}% \mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$, $x,y\in P$. The restricted binary operation on the carrier set of $P$ is a binary operation $\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}:\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x,y}\right)\mapsto% \mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ such that if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(% xy}\right)$, and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\cdot y}\right)$ if and only if there is a canonical left unit $\boldsymbol{\uplambda}_{y}=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yy^{-1}}\right)$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\boldsymbol{\uplambda}_{y}}\right)=x$ . The core $P\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left[\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}}\right]$ of $P$ is $P$ with $\mathfrak{m}$ replaced by $\boldsymbol{\mathsf{m}}$.
Definition 4.4. Let $P$ be a magmoid, $x\in P$. A pseudoinverse of $x$ is some $x^{\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(-1}\right)}\in P$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(-1}\right)}}% \right)\in\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\lambda}\right\}_{x}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(-1}\right)}x}% \right)\in\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\rho}\right\}_{x}$. A right preinverse is some $x^{-1}$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{-1}}\right)\in\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left% \{\lambda}\right\}_{x}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{% \lambda}\right\}_{x^{-1}}$, a left preinverse is some $x^{-1}$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{% \rho}\right\}{}_{x}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{-1}}\right)=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{% \rho}\right\}{}_{x^{-1}}$, and a preinverse of $x$ is some $x^{-1}\in P$ such that $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xx^{-1}}\right)\in\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left% \{\lambda}\right\}_{x}\cap\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\rho}\right\}_{x^{-1}}$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x^{-1}x}\right)\in\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left% \{\rho}\right\}_{x}\cap\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left\{\lambda}\right\}_{x^{-1}}$.
Definition 4.1. Let $P$ be a magmoid, $x,y,z\in P$. Consider the following conditions: (S1) If $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)}\right)$ or $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)z}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)}\right% )=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)z}\right)$. (S2) If $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)}\right)$ or if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)}\right% )=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)z}\right)$. (S3) If $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)z}\right)$ or if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)}\right% )=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)z}\right)$. (S4) If $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)}\right)$ or $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)z}\right)$ or if $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)$ and $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)$ then $\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(x\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(yz}\right)}\right% )=\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(\mathopen{}\mathclose{{}\left(xy}\right)z}\right)$. A near semigroupoid is a magmoid satisfying (S1), a left semigroupoid is a magmoid satisfying (S2), a right semigroupoid is a magmoid satisfying (S3), and a (two-sided) semigroupoid is a magmoid satisfying (S4).
Definition 1. Given an open learner $A=(P_{A},I_{A},U_{A},r_{A}):X\to Y$, we define an open game $F(A):\binom{X}{X}\to\binom{Y}{Y}$ as follows: • The set of strategy profiles is $\Sigma_{F(A)}=P_{A}$ • The play function is $\mathbf{P}_{F(A)}=I_{A}$ • The coplay function is $\mathbf{C}_{F(A)}=r_{A}$ • The best response relation $\mathbf{B}_{F(A)}(h,k)=\{(p,U_{A}(p,h,k(I_{A}(p,h))))\mid p\in P_{A}\}$
Definition 1.2. $(H,R)$ is a Quasi-triangular (or QT) Hopf algebra if $H$ is a Hopf algebra and $R\in H{\otimes}H$, called the $R$-matrix, is invertible and such that $(\Delta{\otimes}\operatorname{id})R=R^{13}R^{23},\quad(\operatorname{id}{% \otimes}\Delta)R=R^{13}R^{12},\quad\Delta^{op}(h)=R\Delta(h)R^{-1},h\in H.$ Dualizing we can define, $(H,r)$ is a CoQuasi-triangular (or CQT) Hopf algebra if $H$ is a Hopf algebra and $r:H{\otimes}H\to{\Bbbk}$, called the $r$-form, is a linear functional which is invertible with respect to the convolution multiplication and satisfies for arbitrary $a,b,c\in H$ $r(c{\otimes}ab)=r(c_{1}{\otimes}b)r(c_{2}{\otimes}a),\quad r(ab{\otimes}c)=r(a% {\otimes}c_{1})r(b{\otimes}c_{2}),\quad r(a_{1}{\otimes}b_{1})a_{2}b_{2}=r(a_{% 2}{\otimes}b_{2})b_{1}a_{1}.$
Definition 1.5. A finite tensor category is a locally finite, $\mathbf{k}$-linear, rigid, indecomposable monoidal Abelian category $\mathcal{D}$ with $\mathrm{End}_{\mathcal{D}}\left(\mathbf{1}\right)\cong\mathbf{k}$. Given a finite group $\Gamma$, a (faithful) $\Gamma$-grading on a finite tensor category ${\mathcal{D}}$ is a decomposition ${\mathcal{D}}=\oplus_{g\in\Gamma}{\mathcal{D}}_{g}$, where ${\mathcal{D}}_{g}$ are full Abelian subcategories of ${\mathcal{D}}$ such that $\bullet$ ${\mathcal{D}}_{g}\neq 0$; $\bullet$ ${\otimes}:{\mathcal{D}}_{g}\times{\mathcal{D}}_{h}\to{\mathcal{D}}_{gh}$ for all $g,h\in\Gamma.$ We have that ${\mathcal{C}}:={\mathcal{D}}_{e}$ is a tensor subcategory of ${\mathcal{D}}$. The tensor category ${\mathcal{D}}$ is call a $\Gamma$-extension of ${\mathcal{C}}$. Denote by $[V,g]$ the homogeneous elements in ${\mathcal{D}}$, for $V\in{\mathcal{D}}_{g}$, $g\in\Gamma$. A braided tensor category is a tensor category ${\mathcal{C}}$ with natural isomorphisms $c_{X,Y}:X{\otimes}Y\to Y{\otimes}X$ such that $\alpha_{V,W,U}c_{U,V{\otimes}W}\alpha_{U,V,W}=(\operatorname{id}{\otimes}c_{U,% W})\alpha_{V,U,W}(c_{U,V}{\otimes}\operatorname{id}),$ $\alpha_{W,U,V}^{-1}c_{U{\otimes}V,W}\alpha_{U,V,W}^{-1}=(c_{U,W}{\otimes}% \operatorname{id})\alpha_{U,W,V}^{-1}(\operatorname{id}{\otimes}c_{V,W}),$
Definition 1.1. Let $\epsilon\colon\boldsymbol{\Delta}\to\boldsymbol{\Delta}$ be the functor $[n]\mapsto[n]\star[n]^{\text{o}}$. The edgewise subdivision $\text{esd}(X)$ of a simplicial set $S$ is defined to be the composite $\epsilon^{*}S$. If $\mathcal{C}$ is an $\infty$-category, we define $\text{Tw}(\mathcal{C})$ to be the simplicial set $\epsilon^{*}\mathcal{C}$. The $n$-simplices of $\text{Tw}(\mathcal{C})$ are, in particular, determined as $\text{Tw}(\mathcal{C})_{n}\cong\textbf{sSet}([n],\text{Tw}(\mathcal{C}))=% \textbf{sSet}([n]\star[n]^{\text{o}},\mathcal{C}).$
Definition 1.2. Let $F:\mathcal{C}^{\text{o}}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be a functor; when it exists, the end of $F$ is the limit $\int_{C}F:=\lim_{\text{Tw}(\mathcal{C})}(F\cdot\Sigma)$ Dually, when it exists, the coend of $F$ is the colimit $\int^{C}F:=\operatorname*{colim}_{\text{Tw}(\mathcal{C})}(F\cdot\Sigma)$
Definition \thedfn. We call $\Theta$ non-degenerate if, for all finite $F\subseteq\mathbb{P}$, $F\text{ is $\Theta^{\leq}$-near}\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad\widehat{\Theta}_{F}% \neq\emptyset.$
Definition \thedfn. We call $S\subseteq\mathbb{P}$ linked if $\{p,q\}$ is $\Theta^{\leq}$-near, for all $p,q\in S$.
Definition \thedfn. We call $\mathbb{P}\subseteq\mathcal{P}(X)$ a $T_{1}$ family if, for all $x,y\in X$, $x\neq y\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad\exists O,N\in\mathbb{P}\ (x\in O\setminus N% \text{ and }y\in N\setminus O).$
Definition \thedfn. We call $C\subseteq\mathbb{P}$ a $\leq$-cover if, for all $p,q\in\mathbb{P}$, $p\leq q\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad p^{\geq}\cap C^{\geq}\subseteq q^{\geq}.$ We denote the collection of all $\leq$-covers by $\mathcal{C}_{\leq}(\mathbb{P})=\{C\subseteq\mathbb{P}:C\text{ is a $\leq$-% cover}.\}$
Definition \thedfn. We call $\Theta$ star-regular if $\forall p\in\mathbb{P}\ \forall C\in\Theta\ \exists D\in\Theta\ (Dp% \vartriangleleft C).$
Definition \thedfn. We say $\Theta\subseteq\mathcal{P}(\mathcal{P}(X))$ is compatible with the topology of $X$ if every $x\in X$ has $(\bigcup C_{x})_{C\in\Theta}$ as a neighbourhood base.
Definition \thedfn. We call $\Theta$ weakly admissible if $\{p\}$ is $\Theta$-near whenever $p^{\leq}\neq\mathbb{P}$.
Definition \thedfn. Consider the following conditions on $S\subseteq\mathbb{P}$. $\displaystyle\forall C\in\Theta\ (C\cap S\neq\emptyset).$ $\displaystyle\forall s\in S$ $\displaystyle\exists C\in\Theta\ (C\cap S\leq s).$
Definition \thedfn. We call $S\subseteq\mathbb{P}$ $\Theta$-near if $\exists D\notin\Theta\ \forall s\in S\ (D\cup\{s\}\in\Theta).$
Definition \thedfn. For any $C\subseteq\mathbb{P}$ and $p\in\mathbb{P}$, the $C$-star of $p$ is given by $Cp=\{c\in C:\{c,p\}\text{ is $\Theta^{\leq}$-near}\}.$
Definition \thedfn. We call $\Theta\subseteq\mathcal{P}(\mathcal{P}(X))$ locally uniform if $\forall x\in X\ \forall C\in\Theta\ \exists D\in\Theta\ (\bigcup(D*\bigcup D_{% x})\subseteq\bigcup C_{x}).$
Definition \thedfn. We call $\mathbb{P}\subseteq\mathcal{P}(X)$ a $T_{D}$ family if $\forall x\in X\ \exists O,N\in\mathbb{P}\ (O\setminus N=\{x\}).$
Definition \thedfn. The $\Theta$-spectrum is the space with subbasis $(\widehat{\Theta}_{p})_{p\in\mathbb{P}}$ and points $\widehat{\Theta}=\{R\subseteq\mathbb{P}:R\text{ is a $\Theta$-round $\Theta$-% Cauchy up-set}\}.$
Definition \thedfn. The uniformly below relation $\vartriangleleft$ (or $\vartriangleleft_{\Theta}$) on $\mathbb{P}$ is given by $p\vartriangleleft q\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad\exists C\in\Theta\ (Cp\leq q).$
Definition \thedfn. If $X$ has a basis of relatively compact sets, $X$ is locally compact.
Definition 2.6. We say that an accessible category $\mathcal{K}$ is below $\kappa$, $\kappa$ a cardinal, if $\mu_{\mathcal{K}}<\kappa$. We say $\mathcal{K}$ is sharply below $\kappa$ if $\mu_{\mathcal{K}}\triangleleft\kappa$.
Definition 2.8. Let $F:\mathcal{K}\to\mathcal{L}$ be a functor. (1) The full image of $F$ is the full subcategory of $\mathcal{L}$ on objects $FA$, $A\in\mathcal{K}$. (2) The powerful image of $F$ is the closure of the full image of $F$ under $\mathcal{L}$-subobjects. (3) The $\lambda$-pure powerful image of $F$ is the closure of the full image of $F$ under $\lambda$-pure subobjects (see [adamek-rosicky, 2.27]).
Definition 2.1. Let $\kappa$ be an uncountable cardinal. (1) (a) $\kappa$ is $\delta$-weakly compact if every $<\kappa$-satisfiable theory in $\mathbb{L}_{\delta,\delta}$ theory of size $\kappa$ is satisfiable. (b) $\kappa$ is almost weakly compact if it is $\delta$-weakly compact for all $\delta<\kappa$. (c) $\kappa$ is weakly compact if it is $\kappa$-weakly compact. (2) (a) $\kappa$ is $(\delta,\lambda)$-strongly compact for $\delta\leq\kappa\leq\lambda$ if every $<\kappa$-satisfiable theory in $\mathbb{L}_{\delta,\delta}$ of size $\lambda$ is satisfiable. (b) $\kappa$ is $(\delta,\infty)$-strongly compact if it is $(\delta,\lambda)$-strongly compact for all $\lambda\geq\kappa$. (c) $\kappa$ is $\lambda$-strongly compact if it is $(\kappa,\lambda)$-strongly compact. (d) $\kappa$ is almost strongly compact if it is $(\delta,\infty)$-strongly compact for all $\delta<\kappa$. (e) $\kappa$ is strongly compact if it is $(\kappa,\infty)$-strongly compact.
Definition 2.3. Let $\lambda$ be a regular cardinal. (1) The colimit of a diagram $D:I\to\mathcal{K}$ in a category $\mathcal{K}$ is $\lambda$-directed if the underlying poset $I$ is $\lambda$-directed, i.e. any $J\subset I$ with $|J|<\lambda$ has upper bound in $I$. (2) An object $M$ in a category $\mathcal{K}$ is $\lambda$-presentable if the associated hom-functor $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{K}}(M,-):\mathcal{K}\to\operatorname{\bf Set}$ preserves $\lambda$-directed colimits. (3) A category $\mathcal{K}$ is $\lambda$-preaccessible if • it contains, up to isomorphism, a set of $\lambda$-presentable objects, and • any object in $\mathcal{K}$ is a $\lambda$-directed colimit of $\lambda$-presentable objects. (4) A category $\mathcal{K}$ is $\lambda$-accessible if it is $\lambda$-preaccessible and closed under $\lambda$-directed colimits.
Definition 2.7. Let $\lambda$ be a regular cardinal. (1) We say that a functor $F:\mathcal{K}\to\mathcal{L}$ is $\lambda$-accessible if $\mathcal{K}$ and $\mathcal{L}$ are $\lambda$-accessible, and $F$ preserves $\lambda$-directed colimits. (2) We say that a $\lambda$-accessible functor $F$ is below (respectively, sharply below) $\kappa$ if $\mu_{\mathcal{L}}<\kappa$ (respectively, $\mu_{\mathcal{K}}\triangleleft\kappa$).
Definition 3.12. An equivariant $U$-controlled morphism $\phi\colon(M,\rho)\to(M^{\prime},\rho^{\prime})$ is a natural transformation $\phi\colon M\to U[-]^{*}M^{\prime}\ ,$ such that $\rho^{\prime}(g)\circ\phi=(g\phi)\circ\rho(g)$ for all elements $g$ of $G$.
Definition 3.1. [Mac71, Sec. VII. 1. & 7.] A symmetric monoidal structure on ${\mathbf{C}}$ is given by the following data: 1. a bifunctor $(-\otimes_{{\mathbf{C}}}-):{\mathbf{C}}\times{\mathbf{C}}\to{\mathbf{C}}$, 2. an object $1_{{\mathbf{C}}}$ (the tensor unit), 3. a natural isomorphism (the associativity constraint) $\alpha^{{\mathbf{C}}}:(-\otimes_{{\mathbf{C}}}-)\circ((-\otimes_{{\mathbf{C}}}% -)\times{\mathtt{id}}_{{\mathbf{C}}})\to(-\otimes_{{\mathbf{C}}}-)\circ({% \mathtt{id}}_{{\mathbf{C}}}\times(-\otimes_{{\mathbf{C}}}-))\ ,$ 4. a natural isomorphism $\eta^{{\mathbf{C}}}:1_{{\mathbf{C}}}\otimes_{{\mathbf{C}}}-\to{\mathtt{id}}_{{% \mathbf{C}}}$ (the unit constraint), 5. a natural isomorphism (the symmetry) $\sigma^{{\mathbf{C}}}:(-\otimes_{{\mathbf{C}}}-)\circ T\to(-\otimes_{{\mathbf{% C}}}-)$, where $T:{\mathbf{C}}\times{\mathbf{C}}\to{\mathbf{C}}\times{\mathbf{C}}$ is the flip functor. This data have to satisfy the following relations: 1. the pentagon relation, 2. the triangle relation, 3. the inverse relation, 4. the associativity coherence.
Definition 3.8. The coarse structure ${\mathcal{C}}$ and the bornology ${\mathcal{B}}$ are said to be compatible if for every $B$ in ${\mathcal{B}}$ and $U$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ the $U$-thickening $U[B]$ (see (3.1)) lies in ${\mathcal{B}}$.
Definition 3.20. We define the associativity constraint $\alpha^{\mathcal{V}_{{\mathbf{A}}}^{G}}$ by the description above.
Definition 3.6. A $G$-bornology ${\mathcal{B}}$ on $X$ is a subset of $\mathcal{P}(X)$ with the following properties: 1. ${\mathcal{B}}$ is closed under forming finite unions and subsets. 2. ${\mathcal{B}}$ contains all finite subsets of $X$. 3. ${\mathcal{B}}$ is $G$-invariant. The pair $(X,{\mathcal{B}})$ is called a $G$-bornological space, and the members of ${\mathcal{B}}$ are called bounded subsets of $X$.
Definition 3.22. We define the symmetry constraint $\sigma^{\mathcal{V}_{{\mathbf{A}}}^{G}}$ of $\mathcal{V}_{{\mathbf{A}}}^{G}$ by the description above.
Definition 3.10. A morphism $f:X\to X^{\prime}$ between $G$-bornological coarse spaces is an equivariant map of the underlying $G$-sets that is controlled and proper.
